The 71 people attending in 2013 is much lower than the other years. \" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>","leftText":"<p>There is one value that stands out as quite different from the others.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br /><br />In 2013, only 71 people attended.<br /><br />(You heard that the weather was awful that year.)<br />&nbsp;</p>","headerText":""},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"8"},"leftText":"<p>When a value is much smaller or larger than most of the other values in the list, it is called an <strong>outlier</strong><em>.</em><br /><br />If a data set has an outlier, then the mean is <strong>skewed</strong>; in other words, it can be greater or less than what is typical of the values in the list.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"The picnic attendance table shows that in 2013 only 71 people attended the picnic, which is much lower than attendance for other years.  71 is an outlier. It caused the average to be lower than most of the other values.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":0,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":1,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"9"},"leftText":"<p>When there is an outlier, the <strong>median</strong> might be a better measure of the typical value.&nbsp; Median is the value in the <strong>middle</strong> of the values in a list.</p>","rightText":null},{"settings":{"showAudio":0,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":"0","delayRight":"0"},"leftText":"<p>There are three steps to finding the median:<br /><br />1.&nbsp; List the values from smallest to largest.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"The picnic attendance table.  The first column lists the year.  The second column shows how many people attended.  The table is sorted from smallest attendance value in the first row, to largest attendance value in the last row.  In 2013, 71 people attended the picnic.  In 2010, 125 people attended.  In 2011, 132 people attended. In 2012, 140 people attended. In 2014, 140 people attended. In 2015, 146 people attended.  \" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>","headerText":"How to Find Median"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":"0","delayRight":"0","audioPath":"10"},"rightText":"<p><img alt=\"The picnic attendance table is divided into two groups of 3. Group 1 lists 2013, with 71 people in attendance; 2010, with 125 people; and 2011, with 132 people.  Group 2 lists 2012, with 140 people in attendance; 2014, with 140 people; and 2015, with 146 people. \" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>","leftText":"<p>2.&nbsp; Divide the list into two equal groups. &nbsp; Make sure the smaller attendance numbers are in the first group and the larger attendance numbers are in the second group.<br /><br />If the list has an odd number of values, then the number in the middle does not go in either group.&nbsp; It will actually be the median of the numbers.<br />&nbsp;</p>","headerText":""},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":"0","delayRight":"0","audioPath":"11"},"leftText":"<p>3.&nbsp; Identify the number in the middle.<br /><br />If there is an even number of values, then there is not a single number in the middle.<br /><br />To calculate the median, add the largest attedance number in the first group to the smallest attendance number in the second group and divide that total by 2.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"The picnic attendance table split into two groups of 3. The last value in group 1 is 2011 with 132 people.  The first value in group 2 is 2012 with 140 people.  The median is in the middle of these two values.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p><p>Median:&nbsp; `(132+140)/2 = 136`</p><p>The median number of picnic attendees during this 6 year period is 136.</p>","headerText":"No number exactly in the middle?  Find the mean of the two closest values."},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"12"},"leftText":"<p>If there is an odd number of values, you don&#39;t need to find the average of two values to find the median.<br /><br />There will be a value in the middle of the list that does not belong in either group.&nbsp; That value will be the median.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">List of values:</span></p><p>1, 2, 2, 3, 4<br /><br /><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Median:</span></p><p><img alt=\"The list of values is divided into two equal groups with 2 values in each group.  The values 1 and 2 from the beginning of the list are in group 1. The values 3 and 4 from the end of the list are in group 2. The  value 2 from the middle of the list is not in either group and is the median. \" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":1,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"13"},"leftText":"<p>When should you use the median to describe a set of numbers instead of the mean?<br /><br />The median better represents the typical value of all the numbers in a set if that set includes an extreme outlier.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":null,"headerText":""},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":1,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"14"},"leftText":"<p>Hmm...&nbsp; Do you have the right number yet?&nbsp;<br /><br />It seems like 136 also might be too low.&nbsp; Three years had an attendance greater than 136.&nbsp; Maybe you need to find the value in the set of numbers that occurs most often and use that to represent the typical value.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"The picnic attendance table shows picnic attendance by year.  The first column lists the year.  The second column shows how many people attended.  In 2010, 125 people attended.  In 2011, 132 people attended. In 2012, 140 people attended.  In 2013, 71 people attended.  In 2014, 140 people attended. In 2015, 146 people attended.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>","headerText":"What value is represented the most?  Finding the mode"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"15"},"headerText":"","leftText":"<p>The <strong>mode</strong> is the value or values that occur&nbsp;most often in a list of numbers.&nbsp;<br /><br />There may be no mode (no number repeated), one mode (one number is repeated),&nbsp; or there may be multiple modes (more than one number is repeated the same number of times).<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">No mode--no number repeats:</span></p><p>1, 2, 3&nbsp; <span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">(Each number is listed only once.)</span><br /><br /><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Single mode--only one number repeats:</span></p><p>1, <span class=\"marker\">2, 2</span>, 3&nbsp; <span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">(2 is the number that repeats, and is the mode.)</span><br /><br /><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Multiple modes--more than one number repeats the same number of times:</span></p><p>1, 2, 2, <span class=\"marker\">3, 3, 3</span>, <span class=\"marker\">4, 4, 4</span>&nbsp; <span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">(2 is repeated twice, but 3 and 4 are both repeated 3 times.&nbsp; They are the modes.)</span></p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":"0","delayRight":"0","audioPath":"16"},"leftText":"<p>There are two steps to finding the mode:<br /><br />1.&nbsp; List the values from smallest to largest.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"The picnic attendance table.  The first column lists the year.  The second column shows how many people attended.  The table is sorted from smallest attendance value in the first row, to largest attendance value in the last row.  In 2013, 71 people attended the picnic.  In 2010, 125 people attended.  In 2011, 132 people attended. In 2012, 140 people attended. In 2014, 140 people attended. In 2015, 146 people attended.  \" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":"0","delayRight":"0","audioPath":"17"},"leftText":"<p>2.&nbsp; Look at the numbers to see which value or values is listed the most times.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"The picnic attendance table sorted from smallest attendance value to largest attendance value shows that the value 140 appears twice.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p><p>Since the value 140 occurs twice, it is represented the most times.&nbsp; The mode is 140.</p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":1,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"18"},"headerText":"What do these measures tell you?","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"The picnic attendance table shows picnic attendance by year. In 2015, 146 people attended.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>","leftText":"<p>You&#39;ve found the following measures of central tendency for the picnic attendance information:<br />&nbsp;</p><p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">Mean&nbsp; 126</p><p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">Median&nbsp; 136</p><p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">Mode&nbsp; 140</p><p><br />It appears that the mode might be the best predictor of attendance to use to ensure that you don&#39;t run out of food, or that you don&#39;t have many leftovers.<br />&nbsp;</p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"19"},"leftText":"<p>The low number of attendees in 2013 influenced the mean, but it also influenced the calculations for median and mode as well.&nbsp;<br /><br />Did bad weather really keep everyone away?&nbsp; Could the same thing happen this year?&nbsp; The committee should verify&nbsp;the reason for the low attendance that year before making a final decision about how much food to order.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"The picnic attendance table shows that only 71 people attended the picnic in 2013.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":0,"showHeader":1,"hideRightPanel":1,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"20"},"leftText":"<p>You may be thinking that you could have looked at the list of attendees and made a prediction about how much food to order without all of the calculations.<br /><br />And that might be true!<br /><br />But imagine a more complicated situation with many more values to consider.&nbsp; Or a situation that was more life-and-death than ordering sandwiches.<br /><br />City planners, school administrators, business owners, government agents and many other professionals often have to make predictions about the future based on historical information.<br /><br />That&#39;s why understanding these types of measures is important!<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":null,"headerText":"Putting it all together"},{"settings":{"showAudio":0,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":1,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0},"leftText":"<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-summary\"><tbody><tr><th scope=\"col\">Remember!</th></tr><tr><td><ul><li><strong>Mean:</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; Add the list of values and divide by the number of values in the list.</li><li><strong>Median:&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp; Order the list of values and find the value in the middle.&nbsp; If the list has an even number of values, then calculate the mean of the two values in the middle.</li><li><strong>Mode:</strong>&nbsp; Order the list of values and find the values that are listed the most often.&nbsp; If no value is listed more than once, then there is no mode.&nbsp; There can be more than one mode!</li></ul></td></tr></tbody></table><p>&nbsp;</p>","rightText":null}],"overviewHeader":"Overview"}
